Proper pattern:
  FILE *fp = fopen("file.txt", "w");
  if (!fp) { handle_error(); }
  /* write to fp */
  if (fclose(fp) != 0) {
      perror("fclose");  /* write error detected at flush */
  }

What fclose does internally:
  1. fflush(fp)      -- write buffer to kernel
  2. close(fd)        -- release file descriptor
  3. free(fp)         -- release FILE struct

Forgetting fclose:
  - Buffered data may be lost on crash
  - File descriptors accumulate until limit (EMFILE)

